-- Hong Kong Stocks Rise on ECB Speculation; Developers Gain
-- B y   C r y s t a l   C h u i
-- 2012-07-05T08:36:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-05/hong-kong-stocks-fall-on-europe-data-before-ecb-meeting.html
Hong Kong  stocks  rose to the highest
level in two months as developers gained on a ratings upgrade
before a meeting today at which the European Central Bank is
expected to cut interest rates to a record low.  Cosco Pacific Ltd. (1199) , which operates a port in Greece, added
1.8 percent.  Henderson Land  Development Co. led property stocks
higher after the sector was upgraded by China Construction Bank
Corp. Sportswear company  Li Ning (2331)  Co. rose 7.3 percent after
founder and Olympic gold medalist Li Ning stepped in as chief
executive officer.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.5 percent to 19,809.13 at the
close after falling as much as 0.4 percent, with 33 shares
gaining on the 49-member gauge. The measure rose to its highest
level since May 15. Volume was about 20 percent below the 30-day
average ahead of the ECB meeting. The  Hang Seng China
Enterprises Index (HSCEI)  of mainland companies added 0.2 percent to
9,702.91.  “The market will be relatively quiet as investors are
taking a wait-and-see approach,” said Cedric Ma, Senior
Investment Strategist at Convoy Asset Management Ltd. “An ECB
interest cut may stimulate the market a bit but we are looking
for more than an  interest rate  cut to buy.”  The Hang Seng  benchmark index  has fallen about 9 percent
from this year’s peak in February amid concern economic growth
is slowing in the U.S. and China as Europe’s debt crisis
spreads. Companies on the gauge trade at 10.2 times estimated
earnings on average through yesterday, compared with 13.1 for
the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and 10.8 for the Stoxx Europe
600 Index.  Europe Stocks  A gauge of service industries in Germany dropped to 49.9,
below an estimate of 50.3, fueling concern Europe’s debt crisis
may be deepening. A services measure in the U.K. fell to an
eight-month low of 51.3 in June from 53.3 the month before,
Markit Economics and the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and
Supply said.  Stocks rose on expectation that the  European Central Bank 
may reduce the benchmark rate 25 basis points to 0.75 percent in
a policy meeting today, according to the median forecast in a
Bloomberg survey of 62 economists.  Cosco Pacific gained 1.8 percent to HK$10.38. Guoco Group
Ltd., a real-estate company that relies on Europe for half of
its revenue, added 2.5 percent to HK$61.60.  Developers gained after China Construction Bank raised the
sector to overweight from neutral.  Stronger contracted sales
this month were the reasoni for the upgrade, analysts Edison Bian and Peter So wrote in an investor note.  Henderson Land (12)  rose 2.6 percent to HK$45.05. Wheelock & Co
Ltd, a Hong Kong-based developer advanced 5.9 percent to
HK$31.30.  Li Ning  Li Ning  surged 7.3 percent to HK$5.03 after founder and
Olympic gold medalist Li Ning stepped in as chief executive
officer. Shares also rose after TPG Capital, one of the
retailer’s shareholders, said it may boost investment if the
company needs more capital.  Hang Seng Index futures declined 0.7 percent to 19,882. The
 HSI Volatility Index (VHSI)  rose 0.3 percent to 18.59, indicating
traders expect a swing of about 5.3 percent in the benchmark
index during the next 30 days.  Foxconn International Holdings Ltd. (2038)  retreated 1.1 percent
to HK$2.68 after Vice President Terry Cheng unexpectedly
resigned during the cellphone maker’s push to revive earnings.
He stepped down less than a third of the way into his three-year
contract, according to a company statement yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
